The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                               The City Diary 
                Modern High School for Girls moved the high court on Friday for permission to operate school buses older than 15 years after July 31. The court had banned commercial vehicles older than 15 years in the city from July 31. The school  five of its seven buses are over 15 years old  claimed in the petition that buses that ferry students are not commercial vehicles. The plea is likely to be heard by a division bench next week.     The Sealdah-Jaipur bi-weekly summer special will make 15 additional trips between Sealdah and Jaipur. The train will leave Sealdah on all Mondays and Wednesdays in July and August. The schedule remains the same, railway officials said.    The high court on Friday asked Sourav Bhattacharya, 25, of Hazra Road to live in his in-laws house at Regent Park with his wife, Sonia, 23, for at least 15 days at a stretch.  After that Sourav will rent a house and stay there with his wife so that his family members cannot interfere in their daily life, the division bench of Justice A.K. Talukdar and Justice P.S. Dutta said. Sonias lawyer said the court felt that family intervention had strained the couples relations.    Services on the Sonarpur-Canning line of Eastern Railways Sealdah South section were disrupted for four hours from 2.50am on Friday because of theft of 60 metres of overhead wires between Taldi and Canning stations. Railway sources said three tower vans were sent to the site for repairs. Four Up trains and one Down train were cancelled.     The implementation of the state pay commissions recommendations has increased the annual deficit in the civic budget by Rs 180 crore. On Friday, mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharyya tabled the Calcutta Municipal Corporation budget of Rs 2151.85 crore for 2009-10, with a total deficit of Rs 236 crore. No new charges have been imposed.     A lecture and interactive session on Management of Schools in India will take place at the Ramakrishna Mission Institute of Culture, Gol Park, on June 20 between 3 and 5pm. The lecture will be delivered by Nita Kumar, Brown Professor of History, Claremont McKenna College, California.    Master of Public Systems Management (MPSM), a two-year degree course under Calcutta University (2009-11 session), will be inaugurated at the Indian Institute of Social Welfare and Business Management (IISWBM), Calcutta, on July 10. IISWBM officials said classes would commence from July 13.                                                                                                                                                                
